50|$|However, the XYZ color model presupposes {{specific}} viewing conditions (such as the retinal {{locus of}} stimulation, the luminance {{level of the}} light that meets the eye, the background behind the observed object, and the luminance level of the surrounding light). Only if all these conditions stay constant will two identical stimuli with thereby identical XYZ <b>tristimulus</b> <b>values</b> create an identical color appearance for a human observer. If some conditions change in one case, two identical stimuli with thereby identical XYZ <b>tristimulus</b> <b>values</b> will create different color appearances (and vice versa: two different stimuli with thereby different XYZ <b>tristimulus</b> <b>values</b> might create an identical color appearance).|$|R
